er. Six years later, Shen Baoyuan, a sociology student at Yenching University, arrived in the town to conduct fieldwork on the society that once held sway over local matters. She got to know Lei Mingyuan and his family, recording many rare insights about the murder and the Gowned Brothers' inner workings. Using the filicide as a starting point to examine the history, culture, and organization of the Gowned Brothers, Di Wang offers nuanced insights into the structures of local power in 1940s rural Sichuan. Moreover, he examines the influence of Western sociology and anthropology on the way intellectuals in the Republic of China perceived rural communities. By studying the complex relationship between the Gowned Brothers and the Chinese Communist Party, he offers a unique perspective on China's transition to socialism. In so doing, Wang persuasively connects a family in a rural community, with little overt influence on national destiny, to the movements and ideologies that helped shape contemporary China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBrotherhoodszChinazSichuan ShengxHistoryy20th century. 0aFilicidezChinazSichuan ShengxHistoryy20th century. 0aPower (Social sciences)zChinazSichuan ShengxHistoryy20th century. 0aSecret societieszChinazSichuan ShengxHistoryy20th century. 4a1940s Rural China. 4aChengdu Plain. 4aEarly Chinese Sociology and Anthropology. 4aGowned Brothers. 4aPaoge. 4aSecret Society. 4aShen Baoyuan. 4aSworn Brotherhood Society. 4aYenching University. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360533640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605336423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605336.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete